      Oh Elon
   =20
 =20

Well! That was stupid.=C2=A0
To recap. In April of this year,   Elon Musk announced that he had bought a=
bout 9.2% of the stock of Twitter Inc. He agreed to   join Twitter=E2=80=99=
s board of directors, and then   changed his mind. He offered to   take Twi=
tter private at $54.20 per share and then, to my considerable surprise, act=
ually went out and   lined up $46 billion of financing to do it. Twitter=E2=
=80=99s board of directors   consulted its financial advisers, who stage-wh=
ispered =E2=80=9CSAY YES,=E2=80=9D and it said yes. On April 25, three week=
s after Musk=E2=80=99s first announcement, he   signed a merger agreement t=
o buy Twitter for $54.20 in cash.
Less than three weeks after that, Musk changed his mind. I don=E2=80=99t kn=
ow what happened, really, but=C2=A0three leading explanations are:
=09He wanted to buy Twitter in=C2=A0April, but now it was=C2=A0May, and he =
had moved on to other japes and frolics.=C2=A0=09The stock market had falle=
n, the market for social-media stocks had fallen even further, and the pric=
e of Tesla Inc. stock, which Musk was relying on to pay for Twitter, was al=
so way down. Twitter looked like a bad deal at $54.20, and Musk would have =
to stretch a bit to pay for it, so he decided he didn=E2=80=99t want it.=09=
Musk himself had a story about how Twitter tricked him into buying the comp=
any by lying about how many spam bots were on its platform. This story neve=
r made   even the teeniest bit of sense, we have  talked about it   endless=
ly, and now we never have to again. Bye spam bots!

So Musk=C2=A0canceled the deal,=C2=A0Twitter   sued, and the case was set f=
or trial this month. Now it is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0maybe =E2=80=A6=C2=A0not?   B=
loomberg News reported yesterday:

Elon Musk revived a bid to buy for Twitter Inc. at the original price of $5=
4.20 a share, backtracking on his effort to quit the deal and potentially a=
voiding a contentious courtroom fight.
Musk made the proposal in a letter to Twitter on Monday, according to a fil=
ing with the Securities and Exchange Commission that confirmed a Bloomberg =
report. Shares of Twitter climbed 22% to $52 at the close in New York. San =
Francisco-based Twitter said it received the letter and intends to close th=
e deal at the agreed-upon price, without commenting specifically on how it =
will respond to Musk.

Never mind! We=E2=80=99re=C2=A0back to where we were in April. Which is sti=
ll a very weird place? The world=E2=80=99s richest person decided that Twit=
ter is the =E2=80=9Ctown square,=E2=80=9D humanity=E2=80=99s main forum for=
 public communication, so=C2=A0he=E2=80=99s  going to buy it for himself. =
=E2=80=9CElon Musk is buying Twitter=E2=80=9D was a jarring headline the fi=
rst time, six months ago. Now it is a relief.
Here is Musk=E2=80=99s  letter. Here is Twitter=E2=80=99s  tweeted=C2=A0sta=
tement. Musk=E2=80=99s letter says that he intends to close the deal on its=
 original terms, =E2=80=9Cpending receipt of the proceeds of the debt finan=
cing contemplated thereby, provided that the Delaware Chancery Court enter =
an immediate stay of the action =E2=80=A6 and adjourn the trial and all oth=
er proceedings related thereto pending such closing or further order of the=
 Court.=E2=80=9D
Just reading those words, two obvious avenues for shenanigans will occur to=
 you. The first is that they could all go to court, and Musk could=C2=A0say=
 =E2=80=9Cit=E2=80=99s okay, we=E2=80=99re closing soon, everything=E2=80=
=99s fine, just need to adjourn the trial,=E2=80=9D and Twitter could say =
=E2=80=9Cyep, everything=E2=80=99s great, Musk=E2=80=99s word is good enoug=
h for us, we=E2=80=99ve never had any reason to doubt him,=E2=80=9D and the=
 judge could say =E2=80=9Cokay great, nice meeting you all, now I am going =
to leave immediately on a six-month vacation with no internet reception,=E2=
=80=9D and then they could walk out of court and Musk could say =E2=80=9Clo=
l psych=E2=80=9D and terminate the deal again. This would be exceptionally =
funny, but I do not think it is very likely. I think that Twitter=E2=80=99s=
 lawyers, and the judge, will probably keep an eye on Musk until his check =
clears, and Musk and his lawyers know that, and trying to=C2=A0trick=C2=A0T=
witter into dropping its lawsuit obviously wouldn=E2=80=99t work.
  [1]

The other issue is that Musk=E2=80=99s offer to close is =E2=80=9Cpending t=
he receipt of=E2=80=9D $13 billion of debt financing from his banks, led by=
 Morgan Stanley. Again there are=C2=A0funny possibilities here. Maybe every=
one will show up at the closing and Morgan Stanley will walk in and say =E2=
=80=9Chey guys you=E2=80=99re not going to believe this but we have reason =
to think that more than 5% of Twitter=E2=80=99s users are spam bots, which =
would create a material adverse effect on the company, so we can=E2=80=99t =
close the financing,=C2=A0deal=E2=80=99s off.=E2=80=9D
  [2]
=C2=A0That would be the funniest possible outcome, much funnier than Musk j=
ust changing his mind again.=C2=A0Musk is a business prankster and his anti=
cs are getting old, but for a serious Morgan Stanley banker to show up and =
do the bot routine, with a straight face,=C2=A0would be incredible.
All of this seems unlikely, though, and I assume that the deal will close. =
The stock closed at $52.00 yesterday, very close to the $54.20 deal price a=
nd up 22% from Monday=E2=80=99s=C2=A0close of $42.54. Several reports sugge=
st that the deal=C2=A0might close =E2=80=9Cwithin a matter of days=E2=80=9D=
 or =E2=80=9Cas soon as next week.=E2=80=9D Last night  Musk tweeted that =
=E2=80=9CBuying Twitter is an accelerant to creating X, the everything app,=
=E2=80=9D which sounds exhausting. The app will do everything, but it will =
start with two functions: You can read tweets, or you can be shot on a rock=
et into space. Choose wisely.
Why? Why would you spend this much time and money trying to get out of the =
deal, and be this annoying about it, and then just unconditionally surrende=
r two weeks before trial? One possibility is that it became increasingly ob=
vious to Musk that he was going to=C2=A0lose=C2=A0the trial, and that didn=
=E2=80=99t seem fun, so he seized the initiative (?) by surrendering instea=
d.
  [3]
=C2=A0If this did go to trial he=E2=80=99d have to testify (and be deposed =
this week), his  text messages with his friends  have become public and mor=
e might come out, and the whole thing would be more distracting, unpleasant=
 and embarrassing than he really wanted.
Similarly,=C2=A0Jessica Lessin=E2=80=99s theory is that Musk =E2=80=9Chas b=
igger challenges to contend with elsewhere. Spending hours and hours prepar=
ing for a trial everyone thought he was going to lose didn=E2=80=99t rank h=
igh on the list.=E2=80=9D Musk=E2=80=99s efforts not to buy Twitter were be=
coming too distracting, so he decided to become the owner (and  interim chi=
ef executive officer!?) of Twitter instead to minimize distraction. That se=
ems right. Sure, running Twitter will be distracting and time-consuming, bu=
t in a fun way. Trying to get out of running Twitter was probably fun initi=
ally, but now it has become a drag.
This lawsuit was always going to be tough to=C2=A0settle.=C2=A0You could im=
agine some other set of facts where you might look at it and say =E2=80=9Cy=
es there=E2=80=99s a 50% chance that a judge will order Musk to close the d=
eal at $54.20 per share, and a 50% chance that she won=E2=80=99t and Twitte=
r will get nothing and end up worth $20 per share  or less.=E2=80=9D And Mu=
sk and Twitter could both see that, and they=E2=80=99d want to minimize ris=
k, so Musk would say =E2=80=9Clook fine $40 per share=E2=80=9D and Twitter =
would say =E2=80=9Cyeah that=E2=80=99s fine=E2=80=9D and they=E2=80=99d com=
promise.
But in the real world Musk=E2=80=99s arguments for getting out of the deal =
were really bad, like, not-even-trying levels of bad. =E2=80=9CDoes Elon Mu=
sk Know How Mergers Work?=E2=80=9D   was a headline I wrote last month. He =
had good lawyers and life is uncertain, but the odds were against him. If y=
ou figured Twitter had=C2=A0a 95% chance of winning, then maybe it would ha=
ve made sense to settle for a repriced deal at, you know, $52 or $53 or wha=
tever. But what would that have accomplished? It would barely save Musk any=
 money, or any embarrassment, and he=E2=80=99d still have to own Twitter. A=
nd it would be a mess for Twitter:=C2=A0=E2=80=9CYou were clearly going to =
win in court, and you gave away billions of dollars of shareholder money ju=
st to avoid Elon Musk saying mean things about you,=E2=80=9D shareholders w=
ould say, when they sued Twitter=E2=80=99s directors personally for violati=
ng their fiduciary duties. Also,=C2=A0Twitter has already put the original =
deal to a shareholder vote, and shareholders overwhelmingly (98.6%)  approv=
ed it; a revised deal would require a new shareholder vote, a new proxy sta=
tement, new disclosures, new delays, new risks.
  [4]

So while it was reasonable to interpret Musk=E2=80=99s actions as being an =
attempt to renegotiate the deal at a lower price, that never really went an=
ywhere. There was no lower price to be had. You can see why he tried; as, l=
ike, a poker move, it made=C2=A0sense. Maybe Twitter would get scared and c=
oncede something. Maybe Musk=E2=80=99s bot-fishing expedition would turn up=
 some evidence so that he could get out of (or reprice) the deal. Maybe=C2=
=A0by some random coincidence someone else=C2=A0would discover that Twitter=
=C2=A0was=C2=A0running a gigantic fraud, completely unrelated to Musk=E2=80=
=99s bot stuff, and that fraud would be enough to get Musk out of the deal.=
 (That arguably   almost happened?) Injecting some chaos into this deal inc=
reased the chances of getting Musk out of it, or at least getting him a low=
er price. It just didn=E2=80=99t work. It was a fine gamble, it failed, and=
 Musk, sensibly, moved on.
Now, in the real world, there was an obvious risk to Musk=E2=80=99s strateg=
y of creating chaos and talking trash about Twitter =E2=80=94 saying that m=
ost of its users are fake, that it is a long-running fraud on advertisers, =
  that there was a=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cbroader conspiracy among Twitter executive=
s to deceive the public, its investors, and the government about the dysfun=
ction at the heart of the company=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0to try to get out=
 of the deal. The risk was that he would do a good enough job of talking tr=
ash about Twitter to=C2=A0damage the company, but not good enough to=C2=A0g=
et out of the deal. If Musk went out and=C2=A0caused=C2=A0a material advers=
e effect on Twitter, or a not-quite-material-adverse-effect-but-still-prett=
y-bad, he=E2=80=99d be stuck buying it, but he=E2=80=99d regret it even mor=
e.=C2=A0
I guess that sort of happened? The  Wall Street Journal notes:
Twitter is now arguably in worse shape than it was when Mr. Musk said he wa=
s walking away, buffeted by a deteriorating outlook for digital advertising=
, the emergence of its former security chief as a whistleblower who claimed=
 a range of failures by its management, and uncertainty over the company=E2=
=80=99s future stoked by Mr. Musk himself.
I don=E2=80=99t want to overstate this. Musk=E2=80=99s main=C2=A0approach h=
ere was to argue that Twitter=E2=80=99s users are all fake and it deceives =
advertisers by undercounting bot accounts. You could imagine that argument =
doing real damage to Twitter=E2=80=99s business, if advertisers looked at h=
is evidence and believed him and stopped buying ads. This never happened be=
cause the bot stuff was transparent nonsense,=C2=A0so that=E2=80=99s good I=
 guess, for him, now that he=E2=80=99s buying Twitter again. On the other h=
and there is, you know, the rest of it. That whistleblower testified before=
 Congress, and   got=C2=A0way=C2=A0more attention than he would have withou=
t Musk=E2=80=99s involvement. Twitter=E2=80=99s employees are demoralized b=
y months of fighting to be acquired by a guy who hates them; how many of th=
em will stick around?
And then there is the financing. Musk=E2=80=99s banks, led by Morgan Stanle=
y, have committed to lend Twitter $13 billon to help pay the purchase price=
. They made that commitment =E2=80=94=C2=A0and fixed=C2=A0the terms of that=
 debt =E2=80=94 in April, when social-media stocks were higher, Musk was ri=
cher, credit spreads were tighter, interest rates were lower, and Musk was =
saying nice things about Twitter instead of calling it a massive fraud. Now=
 it is October and that commitment looks awful.   Bloomberg reports:=C2=A0
If terms of the original $12.5 billion financing package
  [5]
=C2=A0remain the same, bankers may struggle to sell the risky Twitter buyou=
t debt just as credit markets begin to crack. With yields at multiyear high=
s, they=E2=80=99re potentially on the hook for hundreds of millions of doll=
ars of losses on the unsecured portion alone should they try to unload it t=
o investors. That=E2=80=99s because they would almost certainly have to off=
er the debt at a steep discount.
And:
=E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s similar to a vegetarian going to a steakhouse: Very l=
imited appetite,=E2=80=9D said John McClain, a high-yield portfolio manager=
 at Brandywine Global Investment Management, referring to investor demand f=
or buyout debt. =E2=80=9CGiven the incremental company specific news flow s=
ince the deal was agreed to -- combined with the meaningful deterioration i=
n the economy -- lenders will be very hesitant to provide financing.=E2=80=
=9D
For comparison, the private equity buyout of Citrix Systems Inc. was signed=
 in January, and last month banks sold most of the $15 billion of debt for =
the deal at prices of   83.5 to 91 cents on the dollar. Similar levels here=
 would leave Musk=E2=80=99s banks with more than a billion dollars of losse=
s.
Ordinarily when banks provide debt financing for a leveraged buyout, there =
is an orderly process for marketing the debt. Between signing and closing o=
f the deal everyone =E2=80=94=C2=A0the banks, the target, the buyer =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0gets together and writes disclosure and marketing documents for th=
e debt. The buyer and the target have a business plan and financial project=
ions that they can pitch to potential investors, and they have meetings wit=
h those investors to drum up enthusiasm. And then the debt is sold=C2=A0bef=
ore=C2=A0the deal closes, so that the banks have the money (from selling th=
e debt) to give to the buyer to pay the purchase price at closing.
You can read Musk=E2=80=99s  debt commitment letter for the deal here. On p=
ages 3 and 4 there is a section titled =E2=80=9CSyndication=E2=80=9D that s=
ays that the banks =E2=80=9Cintend to commence syndication efforts promptly=
=E2=80=9D and sell the debt =E2=80=9Cprior to the Closing Date,=E2=80=9D an=
d that requires Musk to do things like =E2=80=9Censure that any syndication=
 efforts benefit materially from your existing lending and investment banki=
ng relationships,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Ccause the Company to assist in the prep=
aration of customary confidential information memoranda=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=
=9Cother marketing materials,=E2=80=9D try to get the debt rated by ratings=
 agencies,=C2=A0and attend at least one meeting for prospective investors, =
=E2=80=9Cwhich meeting shall not exceed two (2) hours in duration and may b=
e virtual.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
But the letter also says that =E2=80=9Cthe Initial Lenders=E2=80=99 commitm=
ents hereunder are not conditioned upon the syndication,=E2=80=9D and it go=
es on:
Notwithstanding anything to the contrary contained in this Commitment Lette=
r or the Fee Letter or any other letter agreement or undertaking concerning=
 the financing of the Transactions to the contrary, neither the obtaining o=
f the ratings referenced above nor the compliance with any of the other pro=
visions set forth in clauses (a)=C2=A0through (f)=C2=A0above or any other p=
rovision of this paragraph shall constitute a condition to the commitments =
hereunder or the funding of the Facilities on the Closing Date or at any ti=
me thereafter.
Musk agreed to help the banks sell this debt, but=C2=A0even if he doesn=E2=
=80=99t help=C2=A0they still have to put up the $13 billion themselves. He =
didn=E2=80=99t help =E2=80=94=C2=A0he hindered! =E2=80=94=C2=A0and here the=
y are. If Musk and Twitter really are trying to close this deal within a fe=
w days, then the banks will have to provide bridge financing: They=E2=80=99=
ll just lend Twitter the $13 billion of their own money, and =E2=80=9Ctake =
out=E2=80=9D the bridge financing later by doing a bond offering to investo=
rs. Hopefully with some investor meetings and marketing materials =E2=80=94=
 hopefully with Musk at least saying nice things about Twitter again =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0but who knows.=C2=A0
Also, what about the=C2=A0equity=C2=A0financing? Right now Musk=E2=80=99s  =
 committed financing consists=C2=A0mainly=C2=A0of (1) that $13 billion of d=
ebt=C2=A0from Morgan Stanley et al., which they will have to fund, and (2) =
his own promise to put up=C2=A0$33.5 billion of his own money. But he=E2=80=
=99s allowed to syndicate his $33.5 billion too: He can get co-investors to=
 put in money with him, and reduce his own stake accordingly, though if tho=
se co-investors flake he=E2=80=99s still on the hook for the whole $33.5 bi=
llion. And in fact back in May, in the brief period between when he signed =
the deal and when he started flaking on it, Musk   did raise about $7.1 bil=
lion of equity commitments=C2=A0from other investors. (As we   discussed on=
 Monday, plenty of=C2=A0other=C2=A0people were texting him asking to get in=
 on the deal too.)
We have not heard much about those equity commitments in the last few month=
s; when he was trying to get out of the deal for alleged fraud, Musk did no=
t have time to go around marketing it to potential co-investors. But now he=
 could use the money. Like presumably he=E2=80=99s going to text Larry Elli=
son again to be like =E2=80=9Chey you=E2=80=99re still in for $1 billion ri=
ght? Should be fun!=E2=80=9D What will those conversations be like? Are tho=
se equity commitment letters still good?
  [6]
=C2=A0Do those investors still want in? If=C2=A0they=C2=A0back out, will Mu=
sk sue them? Will their defense be =E2=80=9Cyou said publicly that Twitter =
is a huge fraud, come on=E2=80=9D?
Also: Is he going to try to raise=C2=A0more=C2=A0money? Is he going to go o=
ut to potential investors again and say =E2=80=9Cchanged my mind, Twitter i=
s great now, this=E2=80=99ll be fun, can I pencil you in for $1 billion?=E2=
=80=9D We   talked on Monday about Musk=E2=80=99s friend Jason Calacanis, w=
ho was trying to raise a special-purpose vehicle to invest in Musk=E2=80=99=
s Twitter deal,=C2=A0tapping individual investors with a $250,000 minimum. =
(=E2=80=9CWhat=E2=80=99s going on with you marketing an SPV to randos? This=
 is not ok,=E2=80=9D texted Musk.) Will they=C2=A0restart that? Every littl=
e bit helps, no? What does the disclosure document for=C2=A0that=C2=A0inves=
tment look like? =E2=80=9CYes Elon Musk has said that Twitter is a dysfunct=
ional fraudulent conspiracy, but everything is fine now, and it=E2=80=99s a=
n accelerant to creating X, the everything app.=E2=80=9D Choose wisely.
Anyway I=E2=80=99m tired of this and I have a new retirement plan. Every ti=
me this newsletter starts with =E2=80=9CProgramming note: Money Stuff will =
be off tomorrow,=E2=80=9D Musk does something outrageous, and Twitter=E2=80=
=99s stock swings up or down.=C2=A0So=C2=A0I=E2=80=99m going to buy a bunch=
 of Twitter straddles and then take a vacation, while Twitter is still publ=
ic and that trick can still work.=C2=A0I=E2=80=99ll make a fortune.

