       =20
  [1] =E2=80=9CTwitter may ask a court in Delaware, where it filed its suit=
, for protections that would force Mr. Musk to follow through with his new =
proposal,=E2=80=9D  reports the New York Times. Also though I mean =E2=80=
=A6 let=E2=80=99s say they just trusted him and dropped the lawsuit, and th=
en he said =E2=80=9Cpsych!=E2=80=9D and backed out again. They=E2=80=99d su=
e him again, in the same court, and the judge would *not be amused*. This i=
s not a good trick.


  [2] Technically this would leave Musk obligated under the agreement, but =
without the financing he=E2=80=99d only have to pay a $1 billion breakup fe=
e rather than actually close the deal. Obviously there would be arguments a=
bout this =E2=80=94 mainly, arguments about whether Musk intentionally blew=
 up his debt financing and so   has to come up with the money himself =E2=
=80=94 but I will not get into them because this situation seems quite fanc=
iful.


  [3] So Bloomberg reports that Musk=E2=80=99s decision to surrender =E2=80=
=9Cmay have been influenced by almost a half-dozen rulings by Delaware Chan=
cery Judge Kathaleen St. J. McCormick over the last three months that went =
Twitter=E2=80=99s way and frustrated Musk=E2=80=99s efforts to show he had =
legitimate grounds to cancel the deal. =E2=80=98It was pretty clear from he=
r rulings the judge was laser-focused on the agreement and not the stuff Mu=
sk wanted to talk about,=E2=80=99 said Brian Quinn, a Boston College law pr=
ofessor who focuses on merger-and-acquisition disputes. =E2=80=98His grand =
theory involving the bots didn=E2=80=99t seem to be gaining any traction wi=
th her.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D=20


  [4] Meanwhile it was tempting =E2=80=94  I was tempted =E2=80=94 to think=
 that a possible settlement could involve (1) canceling the deal and (2) Mu=
sk writing Twitter a whopping great check ($10 billion??) to get out of it.=
 If Musk didn=E2=80=99t want to own Twitter, it seemed mean to force him, a=
nd certainly a lot of Twitter employees and users are not that jazzed about=
 the company=E2=80=99s future ownership. He could just pay some money to ge=
t out. But if Musk buys Twitter, he only has to put up like  $26 billion of=
 his own money =E2=80=94 the rest comes from debt and  equity financing sou=
rces =E2=80=94 and he *owns Twitter*. If he pays a giant termination fee, h=
e has to put up $10 billion or whatever of his own money, and he *gets noth=
ing*. Better to pay $26 billion for a company than $10 billion for nothing.


  [5] The package is $12.5 billion of debt that will be sold to investors =
=E2=80=94 $6.5 billion of loans, $3 billion of secured bonds and $3 billion=
 of unsecured bonds =E2=80=94 plus a $500 million revolver that the banks w=
ill hold.


  [6] The  form of equity commitment letter is attached to Musk=E2=80=99s  =
securities filing about his co-investors. It says that it terminates on =E2=
=80=9Cthe valid termination of the Merger Agreement.=E2=80=9D Did that happ=
en? Musk did send  three letters terminating the merger agreement, and tech=
nically none of them have been ruled invalid. If his co-investors back out,=
 can they argue that he validly terminated? Can he argue that he didn=E2=80=
=99t?=20


